\section{Introduction.}

Studying the interparticle interactions in a correlated electron system by applying laser pulses is a challenging perspective, which may lead to some states of matter that do not exist in equilibrium. For example, changing the electron-electron interaction from the original Coulomb repulsion to an attraction, can induce an s-wave superconducting state with very high transition temperature,1,2 or the BCS-BEC crossover.2,3

Creation a population inversion in metallic bands corresponding to a negative temperature (T) state.9,10 is one of the way to control the interaction. Such investigation done in work of [Naoto,Hideo] for hipercubic lattice, where was shown that it is possible to induce a population inversion in metallic systems using a properly shaped  half-cycle or monocycle pulses, the system without energy dissipation will thermalize in the negative T state after the pulse. This implies an effective switching of the interaction from repulsive to attractive, since a density matrix $\exp(-H/T)$ for a Hamiltonian $H$ with temperature $T < 0$ corresponds to the one for the inverted $-H$ with $-T > 0$.11,12 

Effective switching of the interaction from repulsive to attractive occur because a density matrix $\exp{-H/T}$ for a Hamiltonian $H$ with temperature $T < 0$ corresponds inverted $-H$ with $-T > 0$.

In this chapter we repeat work [Naoto,Hideo] taking realistic 2d square lattice and focused in transient nonequilibrium dynamics.
By the half-cycle pulse we induce shift in the momentum distribution of the electrons. Selecting the parameters of such a pulse we can achieve half of the Brillouin zone, the system is brought to a negative-T state, this is often (depending on the value of the interaction) leads to change of the interaction from repulsive to attractive.

Model for correlated electrons is the single-band Hubbard model driven by an electric field with the Hamiltonian

The total energy has the origin at zero.

{\bf The purpose of the present work} to study the polarization dependence in the Hubbard model on 2D square lattice under the influence of a laser pulse. In this paper we present the results for $\pi$-pulse.
\clearpage

The vector potential has the form \citet{PhysRevB.85.155124}:

\begin{equation}
A(t)=\frac{A_{max}}{\tau}(t-\tau sin(2\pi t/\tau))
\end{equation}

where $A_{max}$ - amplitude of vector potential; $\tau$ - pulse length.


\begin{figure}[h!]
\begin{minipage}[h]{0.55\linewidth}
\center{\includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{figure/xy/PulseA.eps}} a) \\
\end{minipage}
\hfill
\begin{minipage}[h]{0.55\linewidth}
\center{\includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{figure/y/PulseA.eps}} \\b)
\end{minipage}

\begin{minipage}[h]{0.55\linewidth}
\center{\includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{figure/xy/PulseE.eps}} c) \\
\end{minipage}
\hfill
\begin{minipage}[h]{0.55\linewidth}
\center{\includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{figure/y/PulseE.eps}} \\d)
\end{minipage}

\caption{a,c vector potential and external electric field for diagonal direction; b,d vector potential and external electric field for Y direction}
\label{fig:Pulses}
\end{figure}

In case Y direction of field, the maximum value of the vector potential $A_{max} = \pi$ (Figure \ref{fig:Pulses}a,c). For diagonal direction of field the maximum value of the vector potential $A_{max} =\pi*\sqrt{2}$ (Figure \ref{fig:Pulses}b,d). This allows to shift the momentum distribution in the case of Y-field from $\Gamma$ to Y, in the case of diagonal field from $\Gamma$ to M in the Brillouin zone.



In this paper, we investigate properties of the model:

1) Change in the sign of the interaction under the action of a half-cycle laser pulse;

2) Polarization dependence;

3) Dependence on the pulse amplitude;

4) Dependence on the pulse width.



\clearpage
\section{Total energy and double occupancy.}

\begin{figure}[h!]
\begin{minipage}[h]{0.55\linewidth}
\center{\includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{figure/xy/E_tot_xy.eps}} a) \\
\end{minipage}
\hfill
\begin{minipage}[h]{0.55\linewidth}
\center{\includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{figure/y/E_tot_y.eps}} \\b)
\end{minipage}

\begin{minipage}[h]{0.55\linewidth}
\center{\includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{figure/xy/docc_xy.eps}} c) \\
\end{minipage}
\hfill
\begin{minipage}[h]{0.55\linewidth}
\center{\includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{figure/y/docc_y.eps}} \\d)
\end{minipage}

\caption{a,c total energy and double occupancy for XY direction of pulse ($A_{max} =\pi\sqrt{2}$); b,d total energy and double occupancy for Y direction of pulse ($A_{max} = \pi$).}
\label{fig:E_tot}
\end{figure}

We can observe a change in the sign of the interaction in case of field in the diagonal direction, U=2 and U=3. $E_{tot}>0$ and double occupancy $docc>0.25$ after pulse (Figure \ref{fig:E_tot}).

For a field in the Y direction, we do not observe a change in the sign of interaction.




\begin{figure}[h!]
\center{\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{figure/xy/E_mpi.eps}} \\
\caption{The total energy after the pulse as a function of the magnitude of the vector potential.}
\label{fig:E_tot_A}
\end{figure}

In Figure \ref{fig:E_tot_A} total energy after the pulse ($\tau$=4) as a function of the magnitude of the vector potential for XY and Y field directions. The graph shows that for the field in the diagonal direction there is a positive total energy which means that the sign of interaction has changed. The value of the total energy is maximum when the value of the amplitude of the vector potential is maximal. As the magnitude of the vector potential decreases, the total energy decreases and, for a certain value of the vector potential, the total energy becomes negative. What is in accordance with the article [\citet{PhysRevB.85.155124} (Figure 3)]. When the interaction is increased, the value of the total energy decreases and the range of values of the total energy for the different amplitudes of the vector potential (at least in the range that exists Figure \ref{fig:E_tot_A}), such dependence is shown in [\citet{PhysRevB.85.155124} (Figure 3)]. In Y-direction of the field, there is no change in the sign of the interaction with different values of the vector potential and the Coulomb interaction (U=2,3).

In Figure \ref{fig:E_tot_tau} total energy after the pulse ($A_{max} = \pi$ Y-field; $A_{max} =\pi\sqrt{2}$ XY-field) as a function of pulse width. It can be seen from the figure that for a pulse with width 2(XY field direction), the total energy has a positive and maximum value (red and blue lines), this pulse is also the narrowest in the calculations. With increasing pulse width, the total energy after the pulse can become negative, as seen on the blue line. This behavior was demonstrated in the work [\citet{PhysRevB.85.155124} (Figure 3)].
In the case of a pulse in the Y-direction, the total energy is always negative. With increasing pulse width the total energy goes to a more negative region.



\begin{figure}[h!]
\center{\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{figure/xy/E_tau.eps}} \\
\caption{The total energy after the pulse as a function of the pulse width.}
\label{fig:E_tot_tau}
\end{figure}
